				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Assembly can seem a bit weird compared to pure HL languages.<br /><br />In most high level languages a fixed literal value is a fixed literal value, but if used in a 6502 assembly instruction it's going to be interpreted as an address. If you want it to be a value you have to preface it with '#'. But if you are just defining data, no '#' is needed. (As in a define byte command.)<br /><br />While if you are using a labeled RAM location as a variable, it will work as you expect in an instruction, but prefacing it with a '#' will act almost like an address operator!</div>

